07051nam a22007815i 9780773590854DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735908547 a10.1515/97807735908542doi  a(DE-B1597)656984  a(OCoLC)1394872762  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJC355b.I58 2010eb 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a321.022221 aNerenberg, Karl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDialogues on Intergovernmental Relations in Federal Systems /cKarl Nerenberg. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (96 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGlobal Dialogue on Federalism Booklet Series ;v800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tCooperative Mechanisms and Intergovernmental Relations in Federal Regimes -- tIntergovernmental Relations in Argentina -- tIntergovernmental Relations in Australia: Increasing Engagement -- tCooperation and Coordination in Austrian Federalism -- tAddressing Social and Regional Inequalities in Brazil: Achievements and Ongoing Challenges -- tCanada: Evolution at the Margins of the Constitution -- tEU: Intergovernmental Relations in a Supranational Federation -- tFederal Governance in Germany Between Party Politics and Administrative Networks -- tIntergovernmental Relations in India -- tNigeria: Intergovernmental Relations in a Highly Centralized Federation -- tIntergovernmental Relations in South Africa — Growing Pains of a New System or Multi-level Government at the Crossroads? -- tIntergovernmental Relations in Spain -- tThe Latest Developments in Intergovernmental Relations in Switzerland -- tIntergovernmental Relations in the United States of America: Pervasive, Personal and Opportunistic -- tGlossary -- tContributors -- tParticipating Experts0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2005 a Harvard conference honoured Paul Weiler, originally from Thunder Bay, Ontario, who drafted the Notwithstanding Clause of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms and created the Canada Program at Harvard University. Weiler's Notwithstanding Clause saved the floundering constitutional talks that eventually rebuilt Canada upon the Charter of Rights and Freedoms. In Part One of this book, Weiler lucidly describes his very Canadian legal philosophy, spelling out his original intent in drafting the clause. Joining Harvard in 1979, he set up a Canada Program that has provided the image of Canada held by many future leaders. He reenergized the languishing Mackenzie King Endowment for Canadian Studies and soon Mackenzie King visiting professors were teaching everything from Canadian economics to Canadian aboriginal history. After Weiler's address at the 2005 conference, past Mackenzie King professors spoke on Canada; the second part of this book contains their essays. Many discuss constitutional law or politics but discussions range from economic nationalism to water rights. Readers interested in what Harvard students learn about Canada will find these essays intriguing. Weiler's Canada Program is expansively multidisciplinary and this book is a respectful tribute to both Weiler and to Canada. Contributors include Thomas S. Axworthy (Queen's University), Albert Breton, Alan Cairns, John C. Courtney, Angela Fraschini, John F. Helliwell, Haifang Huang, Richard Johnston, Elena Kagan (Dean of Harvard Law School), Randall Morck (University of Alberta), Joy Parr, Anthony Scott, Laurier Turgeon, and Paul Weiler.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCentral-local government relations. 0aFederal government. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAdam, Marc–A